      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are experiencing a case of \"gibberish,\" a common ailment among the leafy greens. The bottom leaves turning yellow while the top ones remain healthy is a classic sign of poor drainage or overwatering, which can lead to root rot. To fix the soil, you'll need to ensure it has good drainage and is not waterlogged. Consider adding some sand or perlite to the soil to improve its texture and drainage. Also, make sure you're not overwatering your plants; let the soil dry out a bit between watering. Remember, a well-drained soil is the key to happy tomato plants. And don't forget, a little bit of extra care can go a long way in keeping those pesky goblins at bay!",
